text:
​​#историичитателей

читал статьи в этой группе о женщинах и девушках, как их бросали мужья, парни, и задумался: почему с прекрасным полом всегда так поступают? и пришел к выводу, что во всем виноваты они сами. не стоит сразу бурно реагировать и кидаться в меня тапочками, сейчас объясню на своем примере. 
год назад мне приглянулась девушка, и я начал с ней встречаться. прошло некоторое время, и как-то я хотел пригласить ее в ресторан. в тот злополучный день она меня отвергла, потому что ей приглянулся другой парень (типа мачо). она сбежала от меня к нему. 
прошло 6 месяцев, она прибегает ко мне со слезами на глазах и просит о помощи. мол, прости меня, тогда я не осознавала, что делала. когда я посмотрел на нее, мне стало ее жалко. в тот момент ей хотелось помочь. но когда я вспомнил, как она со мной обошлась, всё желание пропало, и она была мной послана далеко и надолго. 
потом я выяснил через друзей и знакомых, что он ее сильно избивал, поэтому она хотела, чтобы я с ним разобрался и принял ее обратно. сейчас вы начнёте меня осуждать, почему я с ней так поступил и не помог? ответ прост: мне сделали очень больно, и я после этого должен ее простить и просто помочь? нет. так не бывает и не будет. 
после этого я пытался найти себе другую девушку, и все повторялось как в первый раз. я потерял всякую надежду найти ту самую, единственную. я не хочу никого оскорбить или обвинить, но мораль всей этой истории такова: дорогие девушки и женщины, пожалуйста выбирайте себе достойных кавалеров. не ведитесь на внешность и первые впечатления, ведь порой лучше узнать его, пообщаться с его друзьями и посмотреть на внутренний мир человека, чем на внешний. и хорошо подумать, нужно ли вам начинать встречаться с этим человеком или связывать себя с ним узами брака.
у меня все. ====================================
из писем в @nemolchi.uz. вы можете отправить свою историю анонимно: https://goo.gl/forms/3nvmqxaflb5dq5b92

#мнение

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
​​#историичитателей

#мне_нужен_феминизм
потому что в свои 16 лет я каждый раз сталкиваюсь с ужасным отношением к себе со стороны мужчин. я живу в этой стране, и меня так и норовят выдать замуж. мои ровесницы уже ищут или имеют женихов. я не позволю этому быть. я не хочу, чтобы меня бросили через год или избивали каждый день за то, что я не убралась дома или захотела работать. ну, или высказала свое мнение. 
каждый раз, когда я говорю что-то феминистическое в какой-нибудь группе, люди начинают со мной спорить, доказывать, что все феминистки – мужененавистницы и, вообще, уже добились своего. их любимое: "чего тебе не хватает?", "сейчас уже никого не дискриминируют", "просто некоторым хочется выделиться", "совсем уже свое место забыли". неужели люди думают, что все на свете действительно так хорошо? кэтколлинг на каждом шагу никого не смущает? абьюз уже давно вошел в норму. даже девочки рядом настроены против меня, неужели я одна вижу эту несправедливость? 
отцы строят дома только для своих сыновей, девочки рождаются, чтобы выйти замуж. мальчикам разрешено и даже предписано быть хулиганами, а девочки должны ходить по струнке. мужчины думают, что могут "учить" или "воспитывать"  нас, запрещать нам и позволять делать что-то. когда я говорю о феминизме, я постоянно слышу в свой адрес: "что ты можешь знать о феминизме и о мире, тебе 16. затаила обиду на бывшего бойфренда и стала мужененавистницей?" в каком месте феминистки уже всего добились? почему люди так агрессивны к феминизму? мне нужен феминизм, потому что оба пола все еще против равенства.
#мне\_нужен\_феминизм потому что: -болельщицы пришли искать мужиков на стадион.
-о боже, это же она для нас нарядилась.
-ты же девочка. -феминизм не нужен.
-феминистки – мужененавистницы.
-тебе же только 16.
-иди голой на пляж.
-таскай мешки.
-ищи себе каблука.

кэтколлинг (от англ. catcalling – производное от «кис-кис», которым обычно зовут кошек) — это вид уличных домогательств, которому подвергаются женщины от незнакомых мужчин. как правило, комментарии, присвистывания или смешки, которые слышит женщина, имеют четкий сексуальный подтекст.
=======================================

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subve elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
happy #bookbirthday @ibizoboi!
☄
☄ editor zoboi (pride, 2018, etc.) lays out the collection’s purpose: exploring black interconnectedness, traditions, and identity in terms of how they apply to #blackteens.
☄
given that scope, that most stories are contemporary realistic fiction makes sense (@ritawilliamsgarcia's humorous “whoa!” which dips into the waters of speculative fiction, is a notable exception). conversely, the characters are incredibly varied, as are the narrative styles. ☄
☄
standouts include the elegant simplicity of #jasonreynolds’ “the ingredients,” about a group of boys walking home from the swimming pool; #leahhenderson’s “warning: color may fade,” about an artist afraid to express herself; the immediacy of #traceybaptiste, author “gravity,” about a #metoo moment of self-actualization birthed from violation; #reneewatson’s reflection on family in “half a moon”; and the collection’s namesake, #varianjohnson’s “black enough,” which highlights the paradigm shift that is getting woke. ☄
☄
in these stories, #blackkids are nerds and geeks, gay and lesbian, first gen and immigrants, outdoorsy and artists, conflicted and confused, grieving and succeeding, thriving and surviving—in short, they’re fully human. no collection could represent the entire spectrum of #blackness, however, the presence of trans, #afrolatinx, and physically disabled characters is missed: a clarion call for more authentic black-centric collections.
☄
a breath of fresh air and a sigh of long overdue relief. nuanced and necessary.” (@kirkus_reviews (starred review)) ✊🏾

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

there are ways to challenge these stereotypes to help everyone — no matter their gender or gender identity — feel equal and valued as people.

point it out — magazines, tv, film, and the internet are full of negative gender stereotypes. sometimes these stereotypes are hard for people to see unless they’re pointed out. be that person! talk with friends and family members about the stereotypes you see and help others understand how sexism and gender stereotypes can be hurtful.

#repost @unwomen

women and girls can do any job--and as we progress into the future, they continue to defy gender roles in various male-dominated industries.

#nomore #breakingthesilence #timesup #metoo #womenrising #girlrising #patriarchy #stereotypes #genderequality

text:
what a pig 🐽 🤬. sofia vergara didn't deserve this.
▫️
this 2010 interview with @sofiavergara and gordon ramsay is uncomfortable to watch in the #metoo era. .
. 
during the interview, conducted by jay leno, the tv chef, @gordongram, repeatedly talked over vergara and mocked her accent. he then made several jokes tinged with sexual innuendos and even touched the actresses upper leg without her consent.
. ▫️
vergara appeared uncomfortable throughout but tried her best to laugh along.
.
the strong reaction to this video and its obvious inappropriateness proves that, nine years later, things might finally be starting to change. in 2016, vergara said that she is used to being objectified, but hopefully one day soon no woman will have to be treated like that or have to learn to brush off such awkward behaviour.
.
#metoo #timesup #enoughisenough #sexualharassment #jayleno #sofiavergara #gordonramsay #creep #creepy

text:
resistência: a história de sabrina bittencourt

olá manxs desse brasil! hoje a nossa dr vai ser sobre essa mulher que é uma ativista, que superou arduamente seus traumas, e tornou-se um símbolo de resistência na luta contra o assédio sexual feminino.
.
sabrina de campos bittencourt, teve uma infância marcada por abusos, desde seus 4 anos de idade sofreu violência sexual, por integrantes da igreja que ela frequentava com seus pais (mórmon), aos 16 ficou grávida de um de seus algozes, mas abortou! .
ela diz: “é algo endêmico essa absurda quantidade de líderes de várias religiões que abusam de crianças, jovens e, principalmente, mulheres. desde os quatro anos fui abusada diversas vezes pelos mórmons da igreja que frequentávamos, contra os quais não foi tomada nenhuma providência. o meu caminho foi traçado a partir da dor do outro e da minha dor. eu sabia desde sempre que tinha privilégios que outros não tinham. então, para poder me curar dessas dores, fiz trabalho social intensamente por 20 anos.”
.
quer continuar lendo? acesse nosso site. link na bio!
.

.

text:
texto por: @raquelcolibri

normalmente nunca pido nada en mis redes sociales pero me parece un caso de extrema urgencia. si veis mis dos ultimas publicaciones de stories podéis comprobar como un partido español que se ha declarado totalmente conservador y que a mí personalmente su discurso me parece anti-feminismo. lleva varios días haciendo campaña en medios y en redes sociales en contra de las feministas, llamándonos feminazis y utilizando la imagen de otras mujeres para hacer creer que nos apoyan. de verdad, este partido cada vez capta más votantes en españa y me da pánico que muchas mujeres se sientan identificadas con su campaña anti-feminismo calificándola de feminista. ante todo, sororidad hermanas, pero esto tenemos que frenarlo antes de que sigan consiguiendo sillas en puestos de poder. antes de que deshagan todo lo que estamos consiguiendo con esta oleada feminista. tengo mucho miedo de que mujeres se sientan identificadas con su discurso. estoy aterrada de que un partido así exista en mi país y esté creciendo por momentos.
repito, podéis verlos en mis dos ultimas stories e informaros al respecto. no vamos a permitirlo. por todas. por las que ya no están y por las que tenemos el poder de cambiar el mundo.
*
*
*
promovamos el hashtag #voxnoesfeminista en las redes sociales.

i’ve been berated, belittled and bullied, simply because i’m a woman, and i know i’m not the only one.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
then, there’s how women are treated in business. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
some of the stories i’ve heard have made me cry, rage and feel physically ill.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
we suffer from society telling us that we should be polite, dainty and unobtrusive. we shouldn’t challenge, make a scene or have differing opinions.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
as a mother, raising a daughter, i say screw that. i’m teaching her to be brave. be bold. be seen. be heard. be respected.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
if that means she’s perceived as rude, then i’ll be rude too for teaching her. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn’s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica’s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

the accounts were suspended because facebook received repos that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan’s app may not have been completely deleted. kogan’s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided ceifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received repos that, contrary to the ceifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending fuher information.

special counsel robe mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal repoed in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
your diaphragm is a large skeletal muscle that sits underneath your lungs and separates your lungs from your abdomen.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
it contracts and relaxes to move air and in and out of your lungs respectively. we can unknowingly adopt dysfunctional ways of breathing that can lead to increased stress as well as abdominal bloating.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
when the diaphragm doesn’t fully contract, it does not fully inflate your lungs. when the diaphragm doesn’t move appropriately, it throws off the pressures in your abdomen and can lead to bloating.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
the diaphragm, when used correctly, can activate the “rest and digest” part of the nervous system, leading to decreased anxiety, decreased blood pressure, and decreased stress hormone levels.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
stars will take activists to the golden globes red carpet

tarana burke, the #metoo founder, will accompany michelle williams on the red carpet.creditwww.justbeinc.org
by cara buckley
jan. 7, 2018
in their push to highlight the problems of sexual harassment and gender inequality, eight actresses at sunday night’s golden globes ceremony are extending their political statements to their plus-ones.

laura dern, amy poehler, susan sarandon, meryl streep, emma stone, emma watson, michelle williams and shailene woodley say that on the red carpet, they will each be accompanied by activists in a range of fields. the move is part of a widening effort by prominent hollywood women, who formed the umbrella group time’s up, to extend the focus on sexual harassment to women marginalized because of class, sexuality, ethnicity or race.

the initiative’s efforts range from the establishment of a legal fund to fight sexual harassment to symbolic statements like wearing black on the red carpet and now inviting activists to the globes.

text:
2018 has been a roller coaster ride for the oppressed and the oppressor, for the helpless and the powerful and for the campaigners and the bashers. from marital rape to homosexuality to #metoo we have come a long way. let us have a look at some of the most important events that india witnessed this year.

#5 triple talaq bill

the long-pending amendment to muslim women bill, 2018, which criminalizes triple talaq, was passed in the lok sabha with 245 mps in favour of the bill, 11 being against it. triple talaq was the practice of a muslim man instantly divorcing his wife by pronouncing the word “talaq” thrice. since 2016, the said practice had come under a lot of scrutinies for being regressive and violating “equality before the law”. the supreme court itself had described instant triple talaq as the “worst form of marriage dissolution”. though the patriarchal aimplb views it as a weapon to penalize men, essentially, it is a provision to empower helpless muslim women. the bill proposes that instant triple talaq will be illegal and void and will attract a jail term of three years for the husband. though the bill is being tainted as “he vs she” and “hindu vs muslim”, in reality, it is a much-needed reform to uphold the rights and dignity of muslim women.

#womenite #tripletalaq #humanrights #equalrights #equalitybeforelaw #2018rewind #highlightsof2018

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
life is a ⭕️.
i’ll meet you at the turning.
post introspection i have realised that
we don’t know nothing about peoples life.
but our intelligence takes a back seat and we don’t realise what we have heard about a person is just someones perception and not fact!don’t we have the responsibility of not blabbering without knowing the real truth?
it can cost someone their friendship,relationship or their career?
realisation only seeps in when it happens with us.
.
let me share an incident ,#newcomer #2009 -
so i was having a bad day and everything was going wrong and it affected my confidence.i reported on my set and gave 3 retakes instead of 1 for a scene and i was made fun of!normal to have a bad day once in a while.why judge?

enacted a dumb ,innocent,docile,uneducated bahu who washed a laptop with detergent.
so basically she is dumb in real life too?wasn’t it very convincing at that point of time which is still trolled and going viral after all these years?
next you do a trial and due to lack of perception achieved then label her “difficult “?
is there not a possibility that something wrong is being spoken about a women either by someone whom she has turned down or by someone who is jealous of her or someone whom she has given back for misbehaving?
is it not possible that  the “info”is a fact but spiced up,so it loses its credibility?

i dint feel the need to share my #metoo stories because i did the needful on the spot ,ouch .. repercussions?reputation at stake?
rumours are spread because of high self image?

character played with covered clothes expected in real life to be a behenji??
character played with short clothes ,does it means less of character??
why is it not normal to be single?why label?
why personal life should be brought into public eyes?
where is the intelligence gone??
why not give importance to our own life and introspect ? 
let’s eat the food on our own plate!
thank you @virdas for putting things right in perspective ..i totally agree with you !

text:
california: 15,781. michigan: 2,564. pennsylvania: 4,414. these were the number of contacts made to the national domestic violence hotline in a period of 6 months. we’re sharing them with you to give you a sense of how many women could be turned away if #presidenttrump is correct on how long this #governmentshutdown will last. 
that’s because the @ndvhofficial was created and is funded by the violence against women act, a #bipartisan piece of legislation first drafted by joe #biden and signed by every president since 1994, which would have been reauthorized had it not been for the shutdown. besides the hotline, #vawa also provides funding to keep emergency shelters across the country open and supports educational programs that teach our police forces how to handle domestic disturbance calls. but with the department of justice closed, there’s no one around to cut the checks. 
and that puts women at risk. 
scroll to learn more about who the callers to the @ndvhofficial hotline are and it becomes clear: these women are our neighbors, our sisters, our daughters. they need us to call our legislators and let them know that #vawa is a priority. and until vawa’s lifesaving funds get pumping again, they need us to call our local #domesticviolence services to volunteer.

#abuse thrives in silence. let’s use our voices to talk about it, to help others through it, to end it.
.
.
.
#nomore #metoo #timesup #action4vawa #supportsurvivors #enddomesticviolence #andnowsherises

text:
.
من با#حجاب کاری ندارم،آقا اگر حجاب نباشه چی میشه؟ 
زنی که بهش گفتن حجاب و بزار کنار،یعنی اندام تو نشون بده بدون تعارف،حالا ابتدای مسیر بی انتهای ظاهرگرایی و#اصالت_لذت افتاده،حالا که افتاد تو دام#لیبرالیسم_فرهنگی که معتقد به این است که در عالم تمام پدیده ها کالا!و قابل خرید و فروش هستند،زن به مثابه کالا تلقی میشه!
کالایی که مانند اپل و پاناسونیک و تسلا باید در بالاترین کیفیت به مرد عرضه بشه!
حالا کمپانی های عظیم مد،آرایش،جراحی های افسارگسیخته،از نوک ناخن پا،با انواع و اقسام کاشت های ناخن تا زیورآلات مچ پا تا آرایش ساق پا کشیدگی پوست و خالکوبی،برداشتن چربی پهلو،عمل لیفت سینه و بازو،تزریق ژل تو اندام و بوتاکس و پروتز لب و چاله چونه، زاویه دار کردن فک و لنز توی چشم و رنگ مو،اکستنشن و هزاران بدبختی و عذاب در قالب#مدرنیته یا همون جاهلیت ثانی سر جنس ریحانه و لطیف زن میارن که چرخ ابر کمپانی های کپیتالیسم بچرخه!
و یا زن رو به نیروی کار ارزان،منشی یا کارگر برای کاهش هزینه تبدیل کنه
بعد زن رو در یک رقابت ناتمام با همجنس خودش برای ظاهری بهتر داشتن قرار میدن که در آن احدی برنده نیست!
وقتی که باید صرف تعالی و سیر به سمت ملکوت بشه،زنی که میتونه مادری بشه که محسن حججی  بپروره!
در تلقی غیر دینی وحید خزائی تربیت میکنه!
بعد چشم که باز میکنی میبینی چهره زن امروز با انجام تمام این کارهای حقنه شده غرب،از حالت عادی عاطفی خود به یک عروسک زشت مصنوعی و بدون عاطفه که صرفاً با فیزیک خود معرفی میشه شناخته شده!
یعنی با زدن حجاب، چنان بلایی به سر زن آوردن که زن امروز نیازمند یک منجیه! 
این میشه که پولساز ترین سلبریتی‌های غرب مثل لیدی گاگا رو فرش قرمز با کت مردونه بیگ سایز میاد که بگه من آلت دست نیستم!
هشتگ های جهانی#metoo در نفی تجاوز راه میوفته 
در کره کمپین های نابودی لوازم آرایش،تظاهرات حقوق زنان رخ میده،مردم پلاکارد بالای سر خودشون میگیرن کهmy life is not your porn
بیایید در مهندسی معکوس فرهنگی و جدال احسن اینو بگید که زن در حجاب ناخودآگاه به تمام پیرامون اینو القا میکنه که من ارزشمندم،و مستحق احترام!
بعد زنه تو برنامه مذهبی قبل از اذان، 70سالشه فقط نوک دماغش بیرونه،از حضرت زهرا خرج میکنه که حضرت به حجاب اهمیت میداد!
یا حضرت زینب تو گودی قتلگاه هم حجاب شو نگه داشت! 
چرا مثل آب خوردن از ائمه خرج میکنید؟
چرا بی دلیل تا قتلگاه میری نادون؟ 
بیا بگو دختر من این کره،اون هالیوود این دختره که رفت سیرجان،این مردا که از حقوق تو میگن زر میزنن،اینا تو رو کالا میبینن،برهنه و دم دست میخوانت!
اینو بگو

text:
sure, “hurt people, hurt people” but what healing comes out of that. pray for him..
.
.
the past 5 days of watching #survivingrkelly, was like having a reoccurring rude awakening that made me aware of the lack of reverence that black women experience within the system (not only in america) in times for justice.
.
. 
it took a 6 part docu-series to shed light on a matter that's been out there in the open for over a decade. the system failed these women. .
.
.
this man, 6 ft tall, preyed on pubescent girls—a time when the development of a person's brain is at its premature state of learning maturity. he took those 'characteristics' to his advantage to lure them in with the idea of being their 'mentor' of becoming a superstar. but instead, groomed, control and exploit them to his dirty desires. he even took pride in these perversions and called himself the "pied piper of r&b." ... the proof is out there. do the research. .
.
.
after his numerous court cases, he took the media attention as an opportunity to export new music as a way to clear his name and create distractions.
.
.
and guess what, it worked. it's been decades since the first trial and he's still a free man as you read this. and it's about damn time he should be held accountable for his disturbing actions.
.
.
.
if the comparisons between bill cosby and r. kelly isn't about the racial inequality between women of color and white women in terms of attaining justice, i don't want to hear about it.
.
.
in conclusion: i can't separate art from artist in knowing that their 'art' foreshadows their wicked perversions and to dance to it will be like dancing in sin. if you can do so, then that's a privilege the victims wouldn't be able to relate to. .
.
.
i pray for nothing but strength and empowerment for all the women who were brave enough to reopen their wounds and speak out. their endeavors wouldn't be in vain. justice will be served. .
.
.

text:
full piece .
.
i once told another woman i was unhappy with the man i was with
she asked me if i considered therapy

i once told a woman he has been verbally abusive to me
she asked if i asked him to stop

i once told a woman he lied and betrayed me
she asked if it was just one time 
i once heard of a woman next door who claimed he abused her
the others silently sighed 
i once heard the police approach in the middle of the night
and a funeral announcement when the day shined its lights

and the women quietly sighed and echoed
'she should have turned a blind eye'
.
.

__

to the women who are unleashing the ropes , taking a stand and speaking up. 
to the ones who listen and act
to the ones who raise a generation that no longer obeys by oppression 
this is for you

@dortomysoul 
_____

text:
bullying can have a major impact on our lives, and how we perform at work and school. i've been bullied as a teenager, and also in my 30s. both times it was pretty awful, and significantly affected my confidence, and triggered depression in my 30s. 
in the workplace, i reported someone's inappropriate behaviour to the bosses, and as a consequence, i was vilified. this was more than a decade ago, and in the era of the #metoo movement, his behaviour was on a par with some of the major hollywood names currently being outed. 
whatever your situation, remember, you are not alone. reach out and talk to someone. you might feel as though no one understands, but bullying is more commonplace than you expect. 
in fact, bullying is on the rise. an acas study from 2015 reveals that workplace bullying costs the uk workforce £13.75 billion per year and there's a 1.5 percent reduction in overall uk productivity because of bullying. 
if you want to watch my latest youtube video, you may click the link in my bio @lucygriffithsdotcom . . . . . .

text:
calling in for a mindset shift 🙋‍♀️🙋‍♀️🙋‍♀️⠀
⠀
i woke up on the wrong side of the bed...probably because it wasn’t my bed 🤣🤣🤣⠀
⠀
#mamascanyouhearme⠀
⠀
we’ve been struggling to get the kids asleep every night...⠀
⠀
and therefore i struggle to get them up and moving...⠀
⠀
i spent hours being kicked and tossed around aubs bed...and she woke up tired.⠀
⠀
oh sweet girl, i get it #metoo⠀
⠀
the morning was a bust, didn’t get my daily dose of me time in which made me super short with the kids and i yelled at the minions, like 3 times in the 20 minutes from waking them to rushing them out the door.⠀
⠀
i sat down on the living room floor and opened my phone and was reminded of last nights mission from our team call:⠀
⠀
sweat today for @juliaoverfield and her son brody. ⠀
⠀
and just like that it all shifted.⠀
⠀
hard is only hard until you put it in perspective. ⠀
⠀
julia and brody are going through some hard today...but they’ll get through it and together as a team we will lift them up in prayer and sweat, because well that’s just what we do.⠀
⠀
it’s more than a business, or a team it’s a community.⠀
⠀
a community i am grateful to be a part of and a community that is joining forces to sweat today and pray for strength for brody and his family. ⠀
⠀
you can do hard things friend 💗⠀
⠀
#esm⠀
#sweatforbrody 
#everysweatmatters

⠀
sweat today for @juliaoverfield and her son brody. ⠀

⁣
listen, this is situation got me so vexed ⁣
i can’t stand a man with a god complex ⁣
child predator, woman beater, rapist⁣
all of the facts in your face can’t escape this ⁣
used to believe i could fly grade school mission ⁣
but now it’s time to take the key up outta the ignition ⁣
times up boy,you and beat the shot clock ⁣
if you support this man then you get blocked ⁣
you’d rather choose ignorance over innocence ⁣
i’m talking little black girls are you listening ⁣
black lives matter you protest the scene ⁣
but when i say “me too”, you think it’s time to make memes ⁣
black men, something just ain’t adding up ⁣
cuz yal should be the first one standing up ⁣
instead, yal lookin real real silent ⁣
when all that does is increase the violence ⁣
but no, not ever, it won’t be tolerated ⁣
could care less about the sales that he generated ⁣
the right side of history is where we all belong ⁣
my life is worth way more than a damn song. ⁣
⁣
instrumental: who dat: j. cole ⁣
💡. ⁣

text:
sasa-curiosa descobrindo novas cores e formatos! ♥️
.
 ler para o bebê é um hábito muito gostoso e de grande importância, o dia dia entre os livros torna-se costume para o mini leitor e irá ajudá-lo no futuro. como professora, torço muito para que a minha adorável florzinha - e sapeca também -, possa ter o mesmo amor pela leitura que nós pais dela ( meu esposo também é um leitor voraz) possuímos. .
📖 livro em japonês sobre os bichinhos e seus sons, era meu e agora passei para pequena.♥️
.
ℹ️ super dica: há no mercado inúmeros livrinhos de plásticos e tecidos ( ótimos para aquela farra no banho também), esses são os mais adequados para crianças pequenas já que eles levam praticamente de tudo a boca, evitando assim possíveis engasgos ou acidentes. .
.
#maeefilha #leitura #education #bilingue #教師 #sakura #metoo #babygirl #japanesegirl #instalove #metoodoll

text:
fanisa, 20 tahun, tangerang. 
i went to this new bar that just opened in jakarta selatan to meet my elementary friends for our annual catch up. in later evening, one of my friends told us to join his friends upstairs and apparently he’s friends with the owner. the owner gave us free drinks. so nice, i thought. 40 minutes later, i was talking to a stranger about something when someone touched and squeezed my bottom. i flinched. i looked and saw the owner, grinning. i froze. my friend came up to me and asked what’s wrong. i told him about what his bar-owning friend did to me. he laughed and said “well...he gave you free drinks. santai aja lah.” i was so mad. i went downstairs to order an uber and as i waited, someone touched my shoulder. it was the owner. “mau kemana?” he said, like he didn’t just harass me a few minutes before. i told him i’m going home, and he said “serius? ini baru jam 12 kali!” and he leaned in and tried to kiss me. i pushed him to the ground and never came back. 
i’m not pretty nor do i fit in social’s beauty standards. how can i still get sexual harassments from time to time? and then i learned that it can happen to literally everyone.  so if you see something, please say something.  learn to speak up and fight
.
.
.
#keepyourhandstoyourself #handsoffproject #againstsexualharassment #metoo #metoomovement #speakup
name: HANDSOFF. PROJECT

text:
wouldn't it be nice if everyday was a good day? well, some days it seems we meet disappointment after disappointment. but that's just that one day. we can start the next day fresh with the determination that come what may we will find some delight and joy out of the day. it can be especially difficult when we are fighting the wows that come from toxic people or toxic places. but it's possible to fight through it.
***

text:
best of 2018:
i began last year with strange mixed feelings when proposed for a job where i felt unsafe, uncomfortable and randomly even slightly abused and disrespected as a woman. i couldn’t even sleep that night and i lost my voice a few days later (it almost never happens to me).
it all turned out in a big scandal and i am glad in the end i listened to my guts and turned the job off before things got worse.
i am also glad that in time i have learned to love myself enough not to desperately seek validation at the cost of my own mental and physical health, silencing my intuition.
saying no and standing for yourself feels too good to go back.
goodbye to you, abusers in the music industry. i have a list with your names on it. 👋
.
.
.
.
#bestof2018 #metoo #musicindustry #stopabuse #stopviolenceagainstwomen #respectwomen #respectyourself #loveyourself #selfesteem #selflove #selfcare #music

it all turned out in a big scandal and i am glad in the end i listened to my guts and turned the job off before things got worse.
i am also glad that in time i have learned to love myself enough not to desperately seek validation at the cost of my own mental and physical health, silencing my intuition.

goodbye to you, abusers in the music industry. i have a list with your names on it. 👋

text:
dinda, 24 tahun, bekasi. 
aku pernah mengalami kejadian saat berada di tempat perbelanjaan suasana sedang ramai , ada segerombolan pria yang berjalan berlawanan arah dengan ku. dari jauh aku sudah melihat dia dengan perasaan yang tidak enak dan orang tersebut kelihatan seperti habis pulang mabuk mabukan , lalu aku melihat dia memandang bagian dadaku secara rendah aku dapat melihat itu sari tatapan matanya dan lidahnya yg menjulur melecehkan lalu saat berpapasan dengan ku dia mencoba untuk mencolek bagian dadaku yang untungnya meleset dan sempat di halau oleh teman di sampingnya . kejadian itu membuat aku malu dan sakit hati .
.
. 
#keepyourhandstoyourself #handsoffproject #againstsexualharassment #metoo #metoomovement #speakup

text:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

tweet_full:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
meysam_zif
.
من با حجاب کاری ندارم،آقا اگر حجاب نباشه چی میشه؟ 
زنی که بهش گفتن حجاب و بزار کنار،یعنی اندام تو نشون بده بدون تعارف،حالا ابتدای مسیر بی انتهای ظاهرگرایی و#اصالت_لذت افتاده،حالا که افتاد تو دام#لیبرالیسم_فرهنگی که معتقد به این است که در عالم تمام پدیده ها کالا!و قابل خرید و فروش هستند،زن به مثابه کالا تلقی میشه!
کالایی که مانند اپل و پاناسونیک و تسلا باید در بالاترین کیفیت به مرد عرضه بشه!
حالا کمپانی های عظیم مد،آرایش،جراحی های افسارگسیخته،از نوک ناخن پا،با انواع و اقسام کاشت های ناخن تا زیورآلات مچ پا تا آرایش ساق پا کشیدگی پوست و خالکوبی،برداشتن چربی پهلو،عمل لیفت سینه و بازو،تزریق ژل تو اندام و بوتاکس و پروتز لب و چاله چونه، زاویه دار کردن فک و لنز توی چشم و رنگ مو،اکستنشن و هزاران بدبختی و عذاب در قالب#مدرنیته یا همون جاهلیت ثانی سر جنس ریحانه و لطیف زن میارن که چرخ ابر کمپانی های کپیتالیسم بچرخه!
و یا زن رو به نیروی کار ارزان،منشی یا کارگر برای کاهش هزینه تبدیل کنه
بعد زن رو در یک رقابت ناتمام با همجنس خودش برای ظاهری بهتر داشتن قرار میدن که در آن احدی برنده نیست!
وقتی که باید صرف تعالی و سیر به سمت ملکوت بشه،زنی که میتونه مادری بشه که محسن حججی  بپروره!
در تلقی غیر دینی وحید خزائی تربیت میکنه!
بعد چشم که باز میکنی میبینی چهره زن امروز با انجام تمام این کارهای حقنه شده غرب،از حالت عادی عاطفی خود به یک عروسک زشت مصنوعی و بدون عاطفه که صرفاً با فیزیک خود معرفی میشه شناخته شده!
یعنی با زدن حجاب، چنان بلایی به سر زن آوردن که زن امروز نیازمند یک منجیه! 
این میشه که پولساز ترین سلبریتی‌های غرب مثل لیدی گاگا رو فرش قرمز با کت مردونه بیگ سایز میاد که بگه من آلت دست نیستم!
هشتگ های جهانی#metoo در نفی تجاوز راه میوفته 
در کره کمپین های نابودی لوازم آرایش،تظاهرات حقوق زنان رخ میده،مردم پلاکارد بالای سر خودشون میگیرن کهmy life is not your porn
بیایید در مهندسی معکوس فرهنگی و جدال احسن اینو بگید که زن در حجاب ناخودآگاه به تمام پیرامون اینو القا میکنه که من ارزشمندم،و مستحق احترام!
بعد زنه تو برنامه مذهبی قبل از اذان، 70سالشه فقط نوک دماغش بیرونه،از حضرت زهرا خرج میکنه که حضرت به حجاب اهمیت میداد!
یا حضرت زینب تو گودی قتلگاه هم حجاب شو نگه داشت! 
چرا مثل آب خوردن از ائمه خرج میکنید؟
چرا بی دلیل تا قتلگاه میری نادون؟ 
بیا بگو دختر من این کره،اون هالیوود این دختره که رفت سیرجان،این مردا که از حقوق تو میگن زر میزنن،اینا تو رو کالا میبینن،برهنه و دم دست میخوان

text:
mima, 20 tahun, jakarta.

pas malem ada acara di salah satu tempat di jakarta pusat, aku sama temen-temen baru sampe lagi di bar tiba-tiba ada cowok usia kisaran 29th, dia datengin aku yang lagi berdiri di bar, terus dia nanya “kesini sama siapa? dan  dia juga  kaya ngomong enjoy yaa sama temen-temen” aku cuma pikir ohh dia manager atau pr sini kali yaa. terus udah tambah malem aku pindah ke table sama temen-temen aku kita ngobrol-ngobrol, tiba-tiba dia datengin aku lagi, dia ngerangkul aku di bagian pinggul (disini aku mulai ngerasa ga nyaman, tapi aku takut buat bilang sama dia) dan sambil nanya-nanya nama aku, aku kuliah dimana dan sampe akhirnya tangannya turun nyentuh bokong aku, sambil tanyain no telfon aku” disitu aku langsung ngejauh dari dia sambil bilang sorry dan ngejelasin aku ga kenal sama dia dan aku ga bisa kasih no tlpn sembarangan, sambil aku lepas tangannya dari pingul aku, (disitu aku takut tapi aku beraniin ngomong kalo aku ga suka di sentuh-sentuh)
.
.
.
.
#keepyourhandstoyourself #handsoffproject #againstsexualharassment #metoo #metoomovement #speakup

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

un año después de que la alfombra roja de los globos fuera un mar de vestidos negros en solidaridad con #metoo y time's up, los trajes de colores volvieron a la gala, aunque algunos asistentes llevaron una cinta en la que decía "timesupx2" para marcar el segundo año del movimiento por la igualdad de género. en la alfombra estuvo la actriz alyssa milano, autora del tuit que volvió #metoo viral. la actriz señaló que en el último año una "hermandad realmente maravillosa de ha formado". pero fue la actriz de "if beale street could talk" regina king la que hizo la referencia más memorable a time's up al resistir los esfuerzos de la orquesta por acallarla y prometer que, en los próximos dos años, todos los proyectos que produzca contratarán un 50% de mujeres. exhortó a aquellos en otras industrias a seguir el ejemplo.

text:
how to improve your feminism in 2019:

there are a lot of posts going around how to improve your body, your mental well being or even your social interactions in the new year and even though all of those are valid: i want to improve something else.
i want to improve my feminism. especially as a white woman. if i want to claim to be an intersectional feminist that needs some work.
1. rethink my bias. - yes. i am biased. very much so to be brutally honest. and that will have to go. 
2. look for information outside of my bubble - i realised a while back that apparently most of the “intersectional” accounts i follow are run by white women. and just hearing people with the same experiences and backgrounds won’t bring me any new ideas. i can wholeheartedly recommend reading @rachel.cargle and going further from there
3. acknowledge that mainstream feminism as a movement very often relied on contributions made by woc we later ignored, erased and appropriated. (think suffragettes)
4. acknowledge that many accomplishments modern feminism celebrates itself for were flawed and racist (again: think suffragettes). white feminists have failed women of colour in many regards and still continue to do so by not acknowledging and accepting their struggle. i don’t want to have any part in that.
5. don’t be offended. i am guilty of feeling uneasy when hearing discussions about how white women are dangerous and harmful or “white feminism” but here’s the thing - all those things making me uneasy are exceptionally true and call me out on behaviours i didn’t even notice. so being offended is the worst reaction there is, it makes change impossible.
6. listen more. speak less. especially when discussing problems not directly affecting me. let those speak who have first hand experience.
7. speak up against white feminists. it’s the least i can do. 
how are you planning to improve yourself this year?
🌈ruth

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn
